NAVIGATE
  Move ships along a path through sea sectors.

SYNTAX
  navigate <ship-spec> <path>
  nav      <ship-spec> <path>

DESCRIPTION
  Moves one or more ships along a sequence of direction steps.
  Ships consume mobility with each step.  A ship must have at least
  1 mobility point to move.

  <ship-spec>  - ship uid, range (0-5), comma list, * for all, ~ for
                 unassigned ships, or a fleet letter (see 'info fleetadd')
  <path>       - string of hex direction letters

  Direction letters:
    u  upper-right      j  right
    n  lower-right      b  lower-left
    g  left             y  upper-left
    h  stop (halt)      v  view oil/fertility at current sector

  Ships can only pass through sea sectors or under bridges.
  A ship at a harbor can load/unload using 'load' and 'unload'.
  Ships at sea recover mobility slowly each update.

  Any planes loaded aboard a carrier or missile sub (see 'info load')
  travel with it — their position updates to wherever the ship ends up
  once the route completes.

  'v' does not move the ship and costs no mobility -- it just reports
  the CURRENT sector's contents relevant to the ship's capabilities:
    - oil exploration boats and oil derricks show [oil:N] (the sea
      sector's oil deposit, same field a land oil field would drain)
    - fishing boats and trawlers show [fert:N] (the sea sector's
      fertility, which fish production draws on)
  Sail an oil exploration boat around checking 'v' at each stop to find
  a rich spot before committing a slower, pricier oil derrick to it.

EXAMPLE
  navigate 0 jjjj           move ship 0 four sectors east
  navigate * h              halt all ships (stop in place)
  navigate 0 njjju          curved path south then northeast
  navigate 0 uuv            move ship 0 two hexes, then report oil/fert there
  navigate 0 vjjv           report here, move 2 hexes right, report there

